  "text": " Everyone's trying to sell you agentic meshes, but they don't understand what they are, and they're not being realistic where they are today in their business. In this video, I'm going to walk you through exactly what an agentic mesh is, how you get there, and realistically hold a mirror up against where you are in your organization to let you know how far you are from an agentic mesh. Everyone's talking about agentic AI right now, agentic workflows, agentic systems, agentic meshes but most of the conversations jump straight to the end state without explaining what an agentic mesh actually is or how organizations realistically get there let's start with the destination an agentic mesh isn't a single ai system it's not a chatbot it's not one impressive demo an agentic mesh is what happens when multiple ai agents each with a role are embedded across workflows and systems and coordinate work between themselves. Each agent has a clear scope, access to specific systems or data, rules about what it can and can't do. The intelligence doesn't come from one super agent, it comes from how those agents interact, hand off work and escalate to humans when needed. The important thing to understand is this, an agentic mesh isn't a product, it's an operating capability and that's why it's so hard to do well. Most conversations about agentic AI start at the mesh, but in reality you don jump straight to a mesh You got to earn it So let rewind and talk about the journey organizations actually go through Stage one AI as an assistant This is where most organizations are today AI is used as an assistant. Chat GPT, co-pilot, prompting, personal productivity. At this stage, humans lead. AI supports. Nothing happens without explicit input. This is useful. It's low risk. But it doesn't fundamentally change how work flows. AI helps individuals do tasks faster. It doesn't coordinate the work. This is where you can get productivity gains, but it's not the end state. Stage two, AI embedded in workflows. Next, AI starts appearing inside processes. It drafts things, routes things, prepares things, flags things, but humans still decide and approve. This is a big shift because AI is no longer just a tool you open. It's part of how work moves through the organization. A lot of enterprises are either here already or moving into this stage now. Have you found one of these stages quite relatable? If so, drop me a comment. Stage three, agents that can act. This is the most important and most skipped stage. Here you start introducing agents that can complete multi-step work with defined boundaries. They don't just start actions, they take actions, but they're deeply integrated into legacy systems. Constrained by rules monitored continuously these ages aren impressive because they autonomous they impressive because they reliable This is where real enterprise value starts to appear and where trust gets built Stage four it starting to get good now because you coordinating agents Only once individual agents are trustworthy do organizations move into coordination. Now you have multiple agents, clear roles, explicit handoffs, shared context. This is where things get hard because coordination introduces new risks. Errors can cascade. Accountability must be clear. monitoring becomes critical very few enterprises are truly here today and even if they think they are they're not and the last stage for now anyway the agentic mesh now we return to the destination an agentic mesh agents coordinate work across domains humans intervene by exception the organization itself starts behaving differently at this point ai isn't just supporting work it's participating in how work gets organized this is powerful and dangerous if you're not ready it's worth pausing here and asking you why would anyone actually want this? Enterprises don't want agentic meshes in my view because they're cool. They want them because work is increasingly cross-functional, decisions span systems, teams and data. Coordination is now the bottleneck, not an execution. An agentic mesh reduces manual handoffs, context loss, decision latency. The real promise of a mesh isn't autonomy. So here's the honest truth. Most enterprises are somewhere between AI as an assistant and AI embedded in workflow and that exactly where they should be The biggest blockers aren models They data quality legacy integration ownership governance operating models designed for autonomy So from the work I've done with large organizations, the pattern's pretty consistent. The companies that make progress don't chase the mesh. They focus on building a deep number of deep, boring, reliable agents in the most painful parts of the business. And that's how you fast track without skipping the steps. In practice, that means picking high-value workflows, not experimenting, integrating agents into real systems early, defining exactly where agents can act versus advise, designing escalation paths before autonomy, treating agents as roles, not features. You don't accelerate by doing more agents. You accelerate by making a few agents trustworthy. Where that foundation is in place, coordination becomes possible, and the mesh emerges naturally. So for me, I know this was a lot, but the takeaway is simple. Agentsic Mesh is a destination. Deep, reliable agents are the journey. So a lot of people are leading first with Agentsic Meshes, but just be wary. Because if someone is pitching you an Agentsic Mesh today, the right question isn't how smart is it? It's how does it behave on a bad day and who owns the outcome? That's where enterprise AI gets real. Hopefully you enjoyed this. I'm always open for more questions. follow the YouTube or my LinkedIn newsletter for more of this. Catch you later.",
